                            <comment id="12739792" author="mikem" created="Wed, 5 Aug 2009 23:30:54 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Here is another example of a query that could do sort avoidance with added code properly taking&lt;br/&gt;
into acount equijoin relationships:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;select * from TENKTUP1, TENKTUP2&lt;br/&gt;
where TENKTUP1.unique1 = TENKTUP2.unique1&lt;br/&gt;
order by TENKTUP1.unique1 = TENKTUP2.unique1&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The optimizer could pick either TENKTUP1.unique1 or TENKTUP2.unique1 as the outermost&lt;br/&gt;
node and then because it knows that TENKTUP1.unique1 = TENKTUP2.unique1 it would know&lt;br/&gt;
that the query also satisfies order by TENKTUP1.unique1 = TENKTUP2.unique1 without doing&lt;br/&gt;
an additional sort.  &lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12739877" author="dagw" created="Thu, 6 Aug 2009 03:14:36 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The second example should probably read&lt;br/&gt;
:&lt;br/&gt;
order by TENKTUP1.unique1, TENKTUP2.unique1 &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
